fields.value: State-Trait Anxiety Inventory (A-State and A-Trait) (CAPS-STAIST CAPS-STAIS and CAPS-STAIT module)

dsDescriptionValue.value:
The State-Trait Anxiety Inventory was developed to provide relatively brief, homogeneous self-report measures of both state (A-State) and trait (A-Trait) anxiety. Item characteristics that were sought in the development of the STAI scales were high internal consistency and ease and brevity of administration. The STAI A-State scale consists of 20 statements that ask people to describe how they feel at a particular moment. Construct validity was the major criterion for including each individual A-State item in this scale. The items selected for the A-State scale had higher mean scores in a priori stressful situations (taking an exam, giving a speech) than in a neutral situation, and lower mean A-State scores in a relaxed situation. In constructing the STAI A-State scale, the essential qualities that were measured were tension, apprehension, and nervousness as these feeling states varied along a continuum of increasing levels of intensity. Low scores were expected to reflect states of calmness and serenity, intermediate scores were designed to indicate moderate levels of tension and apprehensiveness, and high scores were to correspond with intense states of fright and apprehension, approaching panic.

The STAI A-State scale is an indicator for the transitory anxiety that is experienced by patients and clients in counseling or therapy and this scale has been used to measure changes in A-State intensity in experimental research on stress, anxiety, learning. The developer and principal researcher of this scale is Charles D. Spielberger.

STAIST is the combined file with both A-State and A-Trait items. Data for the separate STAIS and STAIT units are also included.

In CAPS/87, al l members of CAPS did STAIS (A-State) before completing STAIT (A-Trait). (In CAPS/86, members of division B did STAIT first, division A did STAIS first.)

See codebook for additional information
